Git

Git

Initializing a Repository

Git Clone VS Git Init

Initializing a Repository

This is where Git stores its database and configuration information, so that it can track your project.

Checking the status of the repository

git status

You can see your currently branch, unstagged files, stagged files

HEAD is git slang for “the branch you’re currently working on”

Basic Workflow

git add [file]

Stage the files to be commited

Basic Workflow

git commmit -m "message"

Once you have staged the files, you can commit

HINT: git commit –amend

Basic Workflow

git push [origin] [branch]

Put your commits with your code on the server

Initial Configurarion

git config --global user.name 'William'

git config --global user.email 'williamjamir@gmail.com'

git config --global color.ui 'auto'

Hands On - Git Lab

git clone git@gitlab.com:williamjamir/example.git
cd example
touch README.md
git add README.md
git commit -m "add README"
git push -u origin master

Usage

Commands from previous image

git reset

Remove the file that is going to be commited

git checkout

Copies files from the stage to the working directory. Use this to throw away local changes.

Commit

source: http://marklodato.github.io/visual-git-guide

Branching

Branches are used to develop features isolated from each other.

The master branch is the "default" branch when you create a repository.

Branching

Create a new branch named "feature" and switch to it 

 git checkout -b feature

Branching

Deleting a Branch

Switch back to master 

 git checkout master

Delete the branch 

 git branch -d feature_x

Branch at remote repository

A branch is not available to others unless you push the branch to your remote repository 

 git push origin

Update

To update your local repository to the newest commit, execute 

 git pull

Merge

To merge another branch into your active branch use 

 git merge

Merge

Comparing files / branchs

 Git diff

Conflicts

In branch-a, you wrote the word "nine," but your friend wrote "eight." 
 
the number of planets are
<<<<<<< HEAD
nine
=======
eight
>>>>>>> branch-a

Git automatically adds conflict markers to the affected areas.
